Project 2 Linear Models for Next-Day Return Prediction

This project tests whether linear machine learning models (OLS, Ridge, Lasso, Elastic Net) can predict next-day stock returns better than simple baselines, under a strict out-of-sample walk-forward evaluation.

Key idea: predicting prices often looks too good because prices are highly persistent. We therefore model returns, which better reflect a realistic forecasting task.

1. Problem Statement

Objective

We evaluate whether linear models can extract predictive signals from historical market data to forecast next-day returns of AAPL.

Why not predict prices?

A model can appear extremely accurate when predicting prices because prices are persistent (tomorrow's price is usually close to today's). This can inflate metrics without providing meaningful predictive value.

Target definition

We predict the next-day log return: $$ y_{t+1} = \log(P_{t+1}) - \log(P_t) $$ All features are constructed using information available at time (t) or earlier.

2. Data Acquisition & Cleaning

Explanation

We download daily close prices from Yahoo Finance for a small universe:

  • AAPL (target)
  • AMZN, MSFT (peer stocks)
  • QQQ and S&P500 (market proxies)

We align all series on a common calendar and remove missing values before feature construction.

3. Feature Engineering

Explanation

We build a supervised learning dataset where:

  • Target $y_{t+1}$: next-day log return of AAPL
    $$ y_{t+1} = \log(P_{t+1}) - \log(P_t) $$
  • Features available at time (t):
    • lagged returns (short-term memory),
    • rolling volatility (risk regime),
    • market proxies returns (broad market information).

All features are constructed so that no future information is used.

Building the feature matrix (X)

We construct a feature matrix using:

  • lagged returns for each asset in the universe,
  • rolling volatility of AAPL returns,
  • rolling mean returns as a simple momentum proxy.

The resulting dataset follows a standard supervised learning structure:

  • rows correspond to dates,
  • columns correspond to engineered features.

After feature construction, all missing values induced by lagging, rolling windows, and target shifting are removed.

X = pd.DataFrame(index=rets.index)

# 1) Lagged returns for each ticker
for t in FEATURE_TICKERS:
    if t in rets.columns:
        for L in LAGS:
            X[f"{t}_ret_lag{L}"] = rets[t].shift(L)

# 2) Rolling volatility (on target returns)
for w in VOL_WINDOWS:
    X[f"{TARGET_TICKER}_vol_{w}"] = rets[TARGET_TICKER].rolling(w).std()

# 3) Optional: rolling mean (momentum proxy) on target returns
for w in [5, 10, 20]:
    X[f"{TARGET_TICKER}_mom_{w}"] = rets[TARGET_TICKER].rolling(w).mean()

# Align X and y and drop NaNs from feature construction + target shift
data = pd.concat([X, y], axis=1).dropna()

4. Baseline Models (Benchmarks)

Before evaluating machine learning models, we define simple baseline predictors to establish meaningful reference points.

A predictive model is only useful if it outperforms these naive alternatives.

Baseline definitions

We consider the following baselines:

  1. Zero-return baseline
    Always predicts a return of zero.
    This corresponds to a "no-signal" strategy.

  2. Last-return baseline
    Predicts tomorrow's return as today's return.
    This is a simple persistence / random-walk assumption.

These baselines provide lower bounds on predictive performance and help assess whether more complex models add genuine value beyond naive assumptions.

In[17]:

Evaluation metrics

We evaluate predictive performance using standard regression metrics:

  • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
    $$ \mathrm{RMSE} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T} (y_t - \hat{y}_t)^2} $$

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
    $$ \mathrm{MAE} = \frac{1}{T}\sum_{t=1}^{T} |y_t - \hat{y}_t| $$

In addition, we report a Directional Accuracy metric, defined as the fraction of times the predicted return has the same sign as the realized return:

$$ \mathrm{DA} = \frac{1}{|\mathcal{T}|}\sum_{t \in \mathcal{T}} \mathbf{1}\big(\mathrm{sign}(y_t) = \mathrm{sign}(\hat{y}_t)\big) $$

where $$\mathcal{T} = \{ t : |y_t| > \varepsilon \}$$ excludes observations with near-zero realized returns (to avoid ambiguous sign comparisons).

In[19]:
def directional_accuracy(y_true, y_pred, tol=1e-6):
    mask = np.abs(y_true) > tol
    return np.mean(
        np.sign(y_true[mask]) == np.sign(y_pred[mask])
    )


def regression_metrics(y_true, y_pred):
    return {
        "RMSE": np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred)),
        "MAE": mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred),
        "Directional Accuracy": directional_accuracy(y_true, y_pred),
    }

5. Linear Models

In this section, we investigate whether linear predictive models can extract useful information from engineered features to forecast next-day stock returns.

Linear models are studied for three main reasons:

  • they are mathematically well understood,
  • they provide interpretable coefficients,
  • their limitations are well documented in financial time series, making them ideal diagnostic tools.

Linear regression framework

We consider the standard linear regression model:

$$ y_t = \beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{t,j} + \varepsilon_t $$

where:

  • $y_t$ is the target variable (next-day return),
  • $x_{t,j}$ are features available at time $t$,
  • $\beta_j$ are regression coefficients,
  • $\varepsilon_t$ is a noise term.

The goal is to estimate the coefficient vector $\boldsymbol{\beta} = (\beta_0, \beta_1, \dots, \beta_p)$ that best explains the relationship between features and returns.

Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)

The Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) estimator minimizes the sum of squared residuals:

$$ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\text{OLS}} = \arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \sum_{t=1}^{T} \left( y_t - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{t,j} \right)^2 $$

In matrix form, when $X^\top X$ is invertible:

$$ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\text{OLS}} = (X^\top X)^{-1} X^\top y $$

Although optimal under strong assumptions, OLS often performs poorly in financial prediction due to multicollinearity, low signal-to-noise ratio, and parameter instability.

Regularization and biasvariance tradeoff

To stabilize coefficient estimates, we introduce regularization, which penalizes large coefficients and controls model complexity.

Regularization intentionally introduces bias to reduce variance, a central concept in the biasvariance tradeoff.

Ridge Regression (L2 penalty)

Ridge regression solves:

$$ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\text{Ridge}} = \arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \left[ \sum_{t=1}^{T} \left( y_t - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{t,j} \right)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 \right] $$

where $\lambda \ge 0$ controls the strength of regularization.

Ridge regression shrinks coefficients toward zero, reducing variance but keeping all predictors in the model.

Lasso Regression (L1 penalty)

Lasso regression introduces an L1 penalty:

$$ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\text{Lasso}} = \arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \left[ \sum_{t=1}^{T} \left( y_t - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{t,j} \right)^2 + \lambda \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\beta_j| \right] $$

Lasso encourages sparse solutions and can set some coefficients exactly to zero, performing implicit feature selection.

Elastic Net (L1 + L2 penalty)

Elastic Net combines both penalties:

$$ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\text{EN}} = \arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \left[ \sum_{t=1}^{T} \left( y_t - \beta_0 - \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j x_{t,j} \right)^2 + \lambda \left( \alpha \sum_{j=1}^{p} |\beta_j| + (1-\alpha) \sum_{j=1}^{p} \beta_j^2 \right) \right] $$

where $\alpha \in [0,1]$ controls the balance between L1 and L2 penalties.

Elastic Net is particularly well suited to settings with correlated predictors.

Roadmap for implementation

In the following subsections, we:

  • implement each model using standardized features,
  • evaluate them under a walk-forward framework,
  • compare their performance to baseline benchmarks.

We start with OLS as a reference model, before introducing regularization.

We start with OLS as a reference linear model. The objective is not performance optimization, but to understand coefficient behavior, prediction noise, and residual structure in a low signal-to-noise setting.

5.2 Ridge Regression

We now introduce Ridge regression, which adds an L2 penalty to the OLS objective. The goal is to stabilize coefficient estimates and reduce variance in the presence of noisy and correlated predictors.

Distribution of predictions (in-sample)

The figure above compares the in-sample distribution of predicted returns produced by OLS and Ridge regression against the distribution of realized returns.

Several key observations emerge:

The distribution of actual returns is wide and heavy-tailed, reflecting the high volatility and low signal-to-noise ratio of daily stock returns.

OLS predictions are already strongly concentrated around zero, indicating limited explanatory power despite the large number of features.

Ridge predictions are even more tightly concentrated around zero, with a sharply peaked distribution.

This behavior illustrates the biasvariance tradeoff induced by L2 regularization:

Ridge regression successfully reduces variance by shrinking coefficients,

but at the cost of increased bias, leading to predictions that collapse toward the unconditional mean.

While Ridge improves numerical stability and mitigates multicollinearity issues observed with OLS, it does not uncover materially stronger predictive signals in this setting. This result highlights the intrinsic difficulty of short-horizon return prediction and motivates further exploration of sparse models (Lasso) and out-of-sample walk-forward evaluation.

5.4 Elastic Net

Elastic Net combines L1 (Lasso) and L2 (Ridge) penalties. It is designed to handle correlated predictors more robustly while still allowing for sparsity.

In practice, Elastic Net often provides a good compromise between coefficient stability and feature selection.

6. Evaluation Framework Walk-Forward Validation

In time-series prediction, evaluating a model using random traintest splits leads to look-ahead bias and overly optimistic results.

Because financial data are ordered in time, the evaluation procedure must:

  • respect temporal causality,
  • use only past information to predict the future,
  • reflect how a model would be used in practice.

For this reason, we adopt a walk-forward (rolling window) validation framework, which is standard in quantitative finance.

Why standard cross-validation fails for time series

In classical machine learning, cross-validation assumes that observations are independent and identically distributed (i.i.d.).

In financial time series, this assumption is violated:

  • observations are temporally ordered,
  • future data must never influence past predictions,
  • statistical properties may change over time.

Random splits therefore introduce data leakage, leading to invalid conclusions.

Walk-forward validation: principle

Walk-forward validation mimics a realistic forecasting process:

  1. Train the model on a fixed-length historical window.
  2. Generate predictions for the next period.
  3. Move the window forward in time.
  4. Repeat until the end of the sample.

At each step, the model is re-estimated using only information available up to that date.

Mathematical formulation

Let $\{(X_t, y_t)\}_{t=1}^T$ denote the time-ordered dataset.

At evaluation step $k$:

  • the training set is $$ \{(X_t, y_t)\}_{t = k - W}^{k-1} $$ where $W$ is the training window length,
  • the model generates predictions for $$ \{X_t\}_{t = k}^{k + H - 1} $$ where $H$ is the prediction horizon.

This procedure ensures that:

  • no future information leaks into the training set,
  • model performance is evaluated strictly out-of-sample.

Design choices

We make the following design choices:

  • Training window ($W$): fixed-length rolling window
    controls the biasvariance tradeoff and adapts to regime changes.

  • Test window ($H$): short forward horizon
    reflects realistic short-term forecasting.

  • Step size: window is advanced periodically
    balances computational cost and stability.

These parameters are chosen to reflect practical constraints rather than to optimize performance.

Implementation overview

We implement walk-forward validation as a reusable function that:

  • iteratively refits the model,
  • stores out-of-sample predictions,
  • aligns predictions with realized returns.

This framework will be used consistently to compare all linear models.

In[]:
TRAIN_WINDOW = 500
TEST_WINDOW  = 1
STEP         = 1
In[55]:
def walk_forward_predict(
    model,
    X: pd.DataFrame,
    y: pd.Series,
    train_window: int,
    test_window: int,
    step: int,
) -> pd.Series:
    """
    Walk-forward (rolling window) prediction.

    At each step k:
      - Fit model on the last `train_window` observations up to time k-1
      - Predict the next `test_window` observations (k to k+test_window-1)
      - Move forward by `step`

    Returns:
      - A pandas Series of strictly out-of-sample predictions aligned with dates.
    """

    
    assert isinstance(X, pd.DataFrame), "X must be a pandas DataFrame"
    assert isinstance(y, pd.Series), "y must be a pandas Series"
    assert len(X) == len(y), "X and y must have same length"
    assert X.index.equals(y.index), "X and y must share the same index"
    assert train_window > 0 and test_window > 0 and step > 0, "Windows and step must be positive"
    assert train_window + test_window <= len(X), "Not enough data for given windows"

    # Storage for out-of-sample predictions
    preds = []

    # Rolling loop
    # start = index position where we begin predicting (after we have enough training history)
    start = train_window

    while start + test_window <= len(X):
        # Define rolling slices
        train_slice = slice(start - train_window, start)
        test_slice = slice(start, start + test_window)

        # Split
        X_train = X.iloc[train_slice]
        y_train = y.iloc[train_slice]
        X_test = X.iloc[test_slice]

        # Fit only on past data
        model.fit(X_train, y_train)

        # Predict future block
        y_pred_block = model.predict(X_test)

        # Store predictions with correct time index
        preds.append(pd.Series(y_pred_block, index=X_test.index))

        # Advance window
        start += step

    # Concatenate all blocks
    y_pred = pd.concat(preds).sort_index()

    # If overlap occurs (when step < test_window), keep the last prediction for each date
    y_pred = y_pred[~y_pred.index.duplicated(keep="last")]

    return y_pred

Comments

Walk-forward evaluation provides a realistic estimate of predictive power. Any model that does not outperform the simple baselines (especially the zero-return baseline) is unlikely to deliver robust value in practice.

The zero-return baseline has zero directional accuracy by construction, since it never predicts a sign. Directional accuracy is therefore mainly informative when comparing non-trivial models.

However, when predictions are used in a simple sign-based long/short strategy, regularized models (Ridge, Lasso, Elastic Net) exhibit a mild directional edge when aggregated over time.

This apparent improvement should be interpreted with caution: the resulting PnL remains highly sensitive to modeling choices and ignores transaction costs, turnover, and execution constraints. As a result, the observed performance does not constitute robust or economically exploitable predictability.

Overall, this highlights the importance of rigorous out-of-sample evaluation: apparent in-sample or aggregated improvements do not necessarily translate into stable and practical trading value.

8. Robustness Checks

The results obtained so far suggest that predictive signals are weak and that regularization improves stability only marginally.

To ensure that these conclusions are not driven by arbitrary modeling choices, we perform a limited set of robustness checks.

The objective is to assess:

  • sensitivity to hyperparameters,
  • stability of model estimates over time.

These checks are standard in empirical time-series analysis and are analogous to stability tests in numerical methods.

Sensitivity to regularization strength (Ridge)

Ridge regression introduces an L2 penalty controlled by a parameter $\lambda$. The optimization problem is:

$$ \hat{\boldsymbol{\beta}}^{\text{Ridge}} = \arg\min_{\boldsymbol{\beta}} \left[ \sum_{t=1}^{T} \left(y_t - \boldsymbol{x}_t^\top \boldsymbol{\beta}\right)^2 + \lambda \|\boldsymbol{\beta}\|_2^2 \right] $$

The parameter $\lambda$ governs the biasvariance tradeoff:

  • small $\lambda$ behavior close to OLS,
  • large $\lambda$ strong shrinkage.

If the results are robust, moderate changes in $\lambda$ should not lead to large variations in out-of-sample performance.

Coefficient stability over time

In financial applications, relationships between predictors and returns are known to vary across time due to regime changes.

To assess stability, we track Ridge coefficient estimates across successive walk-forward training windows.

Large variability indicates that the model adapts to noise rather than capturing stable structural relationships.

Robustness checks confirm the main conclusions of the study.

9. Conclusion & Next Steps

This project investigated whether linear machine learning models can predict next-day stock returns more effectively than simple baselines, under a strict out-of-sample walk-forward evaluation.

Several key conclusions emerge:

  • Daily stock returns exhibit a very low signal-to-noise ratio.
  • Linear models, even with regularization, struggle to extract stable and economically meaningful predictive signals.
  • Regularization (Ridge, Lasso, Elastic Net) improves coefficient stability, but does not lead to consistent outperformance relative to naive benchmarks.
  • Rigorous evaluation is crucial: in-sample improvements do not necessarily translate into out-of-sample value.

Overall, the results highlight the intrinsic difficulty of short-horizon return prediction and the importance of realistic evaluation frameworks in quantitative finance.

Limitations

This study is subject to several limitations:

  • Only linear models were considered.
  • Feature engineering remained relatively simple (lagged returns, volatility, basic momentum).
  • Transaction costs and market frictions were not explicitly modeled.
  • Hyperparameter tuning was intentionally limited to avoid overfitting.

These choices were deliberate, as the goal was understanding rather than performance optimization.

Possible extensions

Several extensions could be explored to build on this work:

  • Non-linear models (tree-based methods, neural networks),
  • Alternative features (order flow, volatility regimes, macro signals),
  • Different prediction horizons (weekly or multi-day returns),
  • Explicit transaction cost modeling,
  • Portfolio-level evaluation rather than single-asset prediction.

Such extensions may help capture more complex structures, but would require even stricter robustness and validation procedures.
